Using only the original Gaussian-smoothed functional of \(\mu\), the ratio becomes a plain quotient of two integrals:

\[
\boxed{\;
\frac{(\Delta\mu * g_\varepsilon)(x)}{(\mu * g_\varepsilon)(x)}
=
\frac{\displaystyle\int_{\mathbb{R}^n}
        \Bigl(\tfrac{\|x-y\|^{2}}{4\varepsilon^{2}}-\tfrac{n}{2\varepsilon}\Bigr)
        g_\varepsilon(x-y)\,\mu(dy)}
     {\displaystyle\int_{\mathbb{R}^n} g_\varepsilon(x-y)\,\mu(dy)}
\;}
\]

where  

\[
g_\varepsilon(z)=\frac{1}{(4\pi\varepsilon)^{n/2}}\,
                 e^{-\|z\|^{2}/4\varepsilon}.
\]

Everything is expressed as integrals of the original measure \(\mu\); no pointwise “\(\mu(x)\)” or distribution notation appears.

Here is the ratio written strictly as functionals of the original measure \(\mu\), **with no smoothing applied to the numerator**:

\[
\boxed{\;
   \frac{\Delta\mu(x)}{\rho_\varepsilon(x)}
   \;=\;
   \frac{\displaystyle\int_{\mathbb{R}^n}\!
          \bigl(\Delta_y\delta(x-y)\bigr)\;\mu(\mathrm dy)}
        {\displaystyle\int_{\mathbb{R}^n}\!
          g_\varepsilon(x-y)\;\mu(\mathrm dy)}
   \;}
   \qquad(\varepsilon>0).
\]

* **Numerator.**  
  \(\Delta\mu(x)\) is understood distributionally:
  \[
    \Delta\mu(x)\;=\;\bigl\langle \mu,\;\Delta_y\delta(x-y)\bigr\rangle\;=\;
    \int_{\mathbb{R}^n}\!\bigl(\Delta_y\delta(x-y)\bigr)\,\mu(\mathrm dy).
  \]
  The test-function \(\Delta_y\delta(x-y)\) “picks out” the second spatial derivative at the point \(x\).

* **Denominator.**  
  \(\rho_\varepsilon(x)=(g_\varepsilon*\mu)(x)=\int g_\varepsilon(x-y)\,\mu(\mathrm dy)\) with  
  \(g_\varepsilon(z)=\bigl(4\pi\varepsilon\bigr)^{-n/2}e^{-\|z\|^{2}/4\varepsilon}\).

No convolution appears in the numerator; it is a single pairing of the measure with the distribution \(\Delta_y\delta(x-y)\).

\[
\boxed{\,\lim_{\varepsilon\downarrow0}\;
        \varepsilon\Biggl|
        \frac{\displaystyle\int_{\mathbb{R}^n}
                \bigl(\Delta_y\delta(x-y)\bigr)\,
                \mu_{t(\varepsilon)}(\mathrm dy)}
             {\displaystyle\int_{\mathbb{R}^n}
                g_\varepsilon(x-y)\,
                \mu_{t(\varepsilon)}(\mathrm dy)}
        \;-\;
        \frac{\displaystyle\int_{\mathbb{R}^n}
                \bigl(\Delta_y\delta(x-y)\bigr)\,
                \mu_\infty(\mathrm dy)}
             {\displaystyle\int_{\mathbb{R}^n}
                g_\varepsilon(x-y)\,
                \mu_\infty(\mathrm dy)}
        \Biggr|\,}
\]

with \(g_\varepsilon(z)=(4\pi\varepsilon)^{-n/2}e^{-\|z\|^{2}/4\varepsilon}\).

\[
\boxed{\;
\lim_{\varepsilon\downarrow 0}\,
\varepsilon\,\Bigl|
\frac{\Delta\mu_{t(\varepsilon)}(x)}{\rho_{\varepsilon}[\mu_{t(\varepsilon)}](x)}
-
\frac{\Delta\mu_{\infty}(x)}{\rho_{\varepsilon}[\mu_{\infty}](x)}
\Bigr|
\;}
\]

\[
\boxed{\;
\lim_{\varepsilon\downarrow0}\,
\varepsilon\,
\Bigl|
\frac{\Delta\mu_{t(\varepsilon)}(x)}{\rho_{t(\varepsilon)}^{\;\varepsilon}(x)}
-
\frac{\Delta\mu_{\infty}(x)}{\rho_{\infty}^{\;\varepsilon}(x)}
\Bigr|
\;}
\]

A purely algebraic rewrite puts the two fractions over a common denominator:

\[
\boxed{
\lim_{\varepsilon\downarrow0}\;
\varepsilon\,
\frac{\bigl|\,
\Delta\mu_{t(\varepsilon)}\,\rho^{\varepsilon}_{\infty}
-\Delta\mu_{\infty}\,\rho^{\varepsilon}_{t(\varepsilon)}
\bigr|}
     {\rho^{\varepsilon}_{t(\varepsilon)}\,\rho^{\varepsilon}_{\infty}}
}
\]

If you want to separate the two sources of error, expand the numerator once:

\[
\varepsilon\,
\frac{\bigl|(\Delta\mu_{t(\varepsilon)}-\Delta\mu_{\infty})\,\rho^{\varepsilon}_{\infty}
      +\Delta\mu_{\infty}\,
       (\rho^{\varepsilon}_{\infty}-\rho^{\varepsilon}_{t(\varepsilon)})\bigr|}
     {\rho^{\varepsilon}_{t(\varepsilon)}\,\rho^{\varepsilon}_{\infty}}.
\]

No additional assumptions or scaling laws are introduced; it is just an exact rearrangement.

