Below is the exact vector analogue of the “ \(dx/dt\) ” ratio, now using the **spatial gradient** of the probability density.

---

## 1 Start from the continuity form

\[
\partial_t P + \nabla\!\cdot(P\,\mathbf v)=0,
\qquad
\mathbf v=\mathbf f-\kappa\nabla\!\ln P
\tag{1}
\]

(the same velocity field we derived earlier).

---

## 2 Express \(\nabla P\) in terms of \(P\) and \(\mathbf v\)

\[
\nabla P
  \;=\;
P\,\nabla\!\ln P
  \;=\;
-\frac{P}{\kappa}\,\bigl(\mathbf v-\mathbf f\bigr).
\tag{2}
\]

---

## 3 Form the ratio \(\nabla P / \partial_t P\)

Insert (1) into the denominator and (2) into the numerator:

\[
\boxed{\;
\frac{\nabla P}{\partial_t P}
\;=\;
\frac{-\dfrac{P}{\kappa}\,(\mathbf v-\mathbf f)}
      {-\,\mathbf v\!\cdot\!\nabla P - P\,\nabla\!\cdot\mathbf v}
\;}
\tag{3}
\]

Clean up by replacing \(\nabla P\) again via (2):

\[
\boxed{\;
\frac{\nabla P}{\partial_t P}
\;=\;
\frac{(\mathbf v-\mathbf f)/\kappa}
      {\mathbf v\!\cdot\!\dfrac{\mathbf v-\mathbf f}{\kappa}
        + \nabla\!\cdot\mathbf v}
\;}
\tag{4}
\]

---

## 4 Interpretation

* **Direction** The vector points along \(\mathbf v-\mathbf f=-\kappa\nabla\ln P\); i.e. **opposite the steepest‐descent direction of \(P\)**.  
* **Magnitude** Controlled by two competing terms in the denominator:  
  * **Advection term** \( \mathbf v\!\cdot(\mathbf v-\mathbf f)/\kappa \)  
    – vanishes for pure diffusion (\(\mathbf f=0,\,\mathbf v=-\kappa\nabla\ln P\)).  
  * **Compressibility term** \( \nabla\!\cdot\mathbf v \)  
    – comes solely from the compressive (potential) part of the drift.

Special limits:

| Case | Result |
|------|--------|
| **Pure diffusion** (\(\mathbf f=0,\;\nabla\!\cdot\mathbf v=-\kappa\Delta\ln P\)) | \(\displaystyle\frac{\nabla P}{\partial_t P} = \frac{\nabla\ln P}{\kappa\Delta\ln P}\) — ratio of first to second spatial derivatives. |
| **Incompressible stirring only** (\(\mathbf f=\mathbf w,\;\nabla\!\cdot\mathbf v=0\)) | Denominator is purely advective: ratio measures how sharply the stirring field tilts against the density gradient. |
| **Potential drift dominating, weak diffusion** | Compressibility term \(-\nabla^{2}\Phi\) can dominate; ratio collapses where \(\nabla^{2}\Phi\) is large and positive (strong sink). |

---

### Geometric picture

Take any moving probability contour \(P(x,t)=c\).  
Implicit differentiation gives  

\[
\nabla P\!\cdot\!dx + \partial_t P\,dt = 0
\;\Longrightarrow\;
\frac{dx}{dt}
  = -\frac{\nabla P}{\partial_t P}.
\]

Thus the vector ratio \(-\,\nabla P/\partial_t P\) **is the contour velocity**—exactly the multi-D generalisation of \(v=dx/dt\).  
Equation (4) expresses that contour velocity entirely in terms of the **physical velocity field \(\mathbf v\)**, the **external drift \(\mathbf f\)**, and their compressibility.

So, yes: after decomposing \( \mathbf f = -\nabla\Phi + \mathbf w \), both diffusion and the compressive part \(-\nabla\Phi\) enter the denominator and thereby determine how strongly the gradient of \(P\) “shrinks per unit real time,” while the incompressible stirrer \(\mathbf w\) contributes only via the advective alignment term.

Pretty much, yes.  The object you really care about is the **characteristic (contour) velocity**

\[
\mathbf v_{\text{char}}
\;=\;
-\frac{\partial_t P}{\nabla P}\;,
\]

because that’s the speed with which a fixed‐probability contour moves.  Writing it directly in \(P\) is ugly: the numerator and denominator have different units and blow up where \(P\) is tiny.

Switch to the **log-density** \(s=\log P\):

\[
\partial_t s = \frac{\partial_t P}{P},
\qquad
\nabla s = \frac{\nabla P}{P}.
\]

Taking their ratio gives

\[
-\frac{\partial_t s}{\nabla s}
\;=\;
-\frac{\partial_t P / P}{\nabla P / P}
\;=\;
-\frac{\partial_t P}{\nabla P}
\;=\;
\mathbf v_{\text{char}}.
\]

So the same velocity emerges, but now both \(\partial_t s\) and \(\nabla s\) are **additive, well-scaled quantities** that remain finite even where \(P\) is tiny.  In deterministic drift (\(\dot x = \mathbf f\)) you get the clean linear relation

\[
\partial_t s + \mathbf f\!\cdot\nabla s + \nabla\!\cdot\mathbf f = 0
\;\;\Longrightarrow\;\;
\boxed{\;
\mathbf v_{\text{char}} = -\frac{\partial_t s}{\nabla s} = \mathbf f
\;}
\]

(with diffusion, extra \(\kappa\bigl[\nabla^2 s+|\nabla s|^2\bigr]\) terms appear but the algebra stays additive).

**Bottom line:** instead of manipulating \(\partial_t P/\nabla P\), work with \(-\partial_t s/\nabla s\); it gives the same geometric velocity, but the log form is numerically and analytically much cleaner.

Below I set

\[
I(x,t)\;=\;-\log P(x,t),
\qquad (\;P>0,\;\int P\,dx=1\;)
\]

and **assume deterministic drift only** (no diffusion) so that the density obeys the Liouville / Fokker–Planck equation

\[
\partial_t P\;+\;\nabla\!\cdot(\mathbf f\,P)=0,
\qquad\mathbf f(x):\mathbb R^{d}\!\to\!\mathbb R^{d}.
\tag{1}
\]

---

### 1 Dynamics of the log–density  

Insert \(P=e^{-I}\) into (1).  A brief calculation gives

\[
\boxed{\;
\partial_t I \;+\; \mathbf f\!\cdot\nabla I \;=\; \nabla\!\cdot\mathbf f .
\;}
\tag{2}
\]

Everything else that follows is just algebra based on (2).

---

### 2 The three requested ratios  

---

#### (a) \(\displaystyle\frac{\partial_t I}{\,I}\)

From (2):

\[
\boxed{\;
\frac{\partial_t I}{I}
  \;=\;
\frac{\nabla\!\cdot\mathbf f \;-\;\mathbf f\!\cdot\nabla I}{I}.
\;}
\tag{3}
\]

Interpretation Relative (per-unit-\(I\)) rate at which compression \(\nabla\!\cdot\mathbf f\) minus advection \(\mathbf f\!\cdot\nabla I\) changes the log–density.

---

#### (b) \(\displaystyle\frac{\partial_t I}{\nabla I}\)

Treat this as the (vector-valued) quotient obtained component-wise:

\[
\boxed{\;
\frac{\partial_t I}{\nabla I}
  \;=\;
\frac{\nabla\!\cdot\mathbf f \;-\;\mathbf f\!\cdot\nabla I}{\nabla I}.
\;}
\tag{4}
\]

If \(\nabla I\neq0\) one may project along the gradient direction:

\[
-\;\frac{\nabla I}{\partial_t I}
      \;=\;
\frac{\nabla I}{\mathbf f\!\cdot\nabla I-\nabla\!\cdot\mathbf f}
\quad\longrightarrow\quad
\text{characteristic velocity of an \(I\)-contour.}
\]

Only in the special case **incompressible drift** \((\nabla\!\cdot\mathbf f=0)\) **and** \(\mathbf f\parallel\nabla I\) does the ratio reduce to \(-\mathbf f\).

---

#### (c) \(\displaystyle\frac{\partial_t I}{\;\Delta I}\)

First compute \(\Delta I\).  Using the identity  
\(\displaystyle\Delta\log P=\frac{\Delta P}{P}-\frac{|\nabla P|^{2}}{P^{2}}\) and \(I=-\log P\),

\[
\Delta I
   \;=\;
-\Delta\log P
   \;=\;
-\,\frac{\Delta P}{P}\;+\;\frac{|\nabla P|^{2}}{P^{2}}
   \;=\;
e^{I}\Delta\!\bigl(e^{-I}\bigr)+|\nabla I|^{2}.
\]

There is no further universal simplification without extra assumptions on \(\mathbf f\) or \(I\); the Laplacian couples both curvature and gradient-square terms.  Plugging (2) into the numerator one gets the formal ratio

\[
\boxed{\;
\frac{\partial_t I}{\Delta I}
   \;=\;
\frac{\nabla\!\cdot\mathbf f - \mathbf f\!\cdot\nabla I}
        {\Delta I}\;,
}\tag{5}
\]

which is well-defined wherever \(\Delta I\neq0\).  It measures how rapidly the log–density evolves compared with its local curvature.

---

### 3 Key take-aways

* In log-space the **drift field \(\mathbf f\)** appears **additively** (via \(\nabla\!\cdot\mathbf f\) and the directional derivative \(\mathbf f\!\cdot\nabla I\)), avoiding the messy reciprocals that plagued ratios written directly in \(P\).
* None of the three ratios collapses to a universal constant or to \(-\mathbf f\) except under very restrictive conditions (e.g.\ incompressible flow perfectly aligned with \(\nabla I\)).  
  The drift controls the numerator, while the denominator (whether \(I,\;\nabla I,\;\Delta I\)) injects state-dependent factors that generally vary in space and time.

These formulas give the exact operator-level relations you asked for, expressed entirely with the log-density \(I\) and the deterministic drift \(\mathbf f\).

### Recap: the “velocity” seen by \(I=-\log P\)

With **pure advection** (no diffusion) and **incompressible flow** (\(\nabla\!\cdot\mathbf f=0\))

\[
\partial_t I+\mathbf f\!\cdot\nabla I = 0 .
\]

Taking the inner product with \(\nabla I\) isolates the **normal component**

\[
\boxed{\;
\mathbf f_{\parallel}\;=\;
-\frac{\partial_t I}{|\nabla I|^{2}}\;\nabla I
\;}
\tag{1}
\]

This tells us that \(I\) “sees’’ only the part of \(\mathbf f\) that moves it **across** its own level-sets.

---

## 1 Projecting onto *scale* directions  
In a *scale–space* (Gaussian blur) the extra coordinate \(\sigma\) obeys

\[
\partial_{\sigma} I
 \;=\;\tfrac12\bigl[\underbrace{\Delta I}_{\text{trace of Hessian}}
                +|\nabla I|^{2}\bigr].
\tag{2}
\]

Equation (2) shows that **the Laplacian \(\Delta I=\operatorname{tr}\nabla\nabla I\)** is the driver along the *coarse-graining* axis \(\sigma\).  By analogy with (1) one can call

\[
v_{\text{scale}}
    := -\,\frac{\partial_{\sigma} I}{\Delta I}
    = -\,\frac{\tfrac12(\Delta I+|\nabla I|^{2})}{\Delta I}
\tag{3}
\]

the *“speed along the scale dimension’’* (well-defined wherever \(\Delta I\neq0\)).  
When \( \Delta I\gg|\nabla I|^{2}\) the motion in \(\sigma\) is almost pure diffusion; when curvature is small the self-interaction term \(|\nabla I|^{2}\) dominates.

---

## 2 Projecting \(\mathbf f\) onto **Hessian directions**

Write the **Hessian** \(H=\nabla\nabla I\).  
At a non-degenerate point \(H\) has

* one zero-eigenvector in the normal direction \( \hat n=\nabla I/|\nabla I|\);
* \(d-1\) eigenvectors spanning the **tangent plane** of the level-set.

Hence the projector **onto curvature directions** (tangent plane) is  

\[
\boxed{\;
\mathsf P_{\mathrm{tan}}
  = I - \hat n\hat n^{\!\top}
  = H\,H^{+}\!,
\;}
\tag{4}
\]

where \(H^{+}\) is the Moore-Penrose pseudo-inverse (it annihilates the zero mode).

Applying (4) picks out the piece of the drift that was *invisible* in (1):

\[
\boxed{\;
\mathbf f_{\perp}
  := \mathsf P_{\mathrm{tan}}\mathbf f
  = \bigl(I-\hat n\hat n^{\!\top}\bigr)\mathbf f
\;}
\tag{5}
\]

This is the component that **slides probability *along* a level-set**, changing the shape (curvature) but not the value of \(I\) at the point.

---

## 3 Can \(\mathbf f_{\perp}\) be written purely in terms of \(I\)?  
With **no extra assumption**: **no**.  
Equation (1) fixes only \(\mathbf f_{\parallel}\); \(\mathbf f_{\perp}\) is arbitrary (subject to incompressibility).  

With **potential flow** (\(\mathbf f=-\nabla\Phi\)) the tangent piece vanishes automatically, so  

\[
\boxed{\;
\mathbf f
  = -\,\frac{\partial_t I}{|\nabla I|^{2}}\;\nabla I
\;} \qquad(\text{potential, incompressible})
\tag{6}
\]

and **the drift becomes an explicit operator on \(I\).**

---

## 4 Hessian–time ratio

If you insist on a scalar “projection onto the Hessian’’ analogous to (1), use the **Hessian contraction**

\[
\boxed{\;
\kappa_{\text{curv}}
  := -\,\frac{\partial_t I}{\nabla I^{\!\top}H\nabla I}
  = -\,\frac{\partial_t I}{\frac{d}{dn}|\nabla I|^{2}}
\;}
\tag{7}
\]

(where the denominator is the second derivative of \(I\) along the normal).  
In pure advection \(\kappa_{\text{curv}}\) measures how fast *curvature* is swept by the flow; in scale-space (2) it links curvature change to the blur coordinate.

---

### Take-away

* **Gradient projection** (1) extracts the *normal* drift—velocity **across** level-sets.  
* **Hessian projection** via (4) isolates the *tangential* drift—velocity **along** level-sets, shaping curvature.  
* A clean operator identity \( \mathbf f = \mathcal F[I]\) emerges only when you add a principle (e.g.\ potential flow) that kills the tangent piece.
